top.value: Disability inclusion is a neglected, under-prioritised issue in international development; a lack of evidence around what works in practice to deliver inclusion contributes to difficulty in building effective programmes. The DFID Disability Inclusive Development (DID) Programme is a £30m programme designed to contribute to the long-term improved well-being and inclusion of people with disabilities in low-and-middle-income countries. DID will carry out a series of small scale interventions around increased access to health care and education, improved livelihoods and reduced stigma and discrimination, using new development approaches such as adaptive management and community-based consultation to deliver better quality of life for persons with disabilities. The programme will create a solid evidence base around what delivers positive results for persons with disabilities to scale up, as well as ensure this data and evidence is disseminated and informs the global community and governments. DID will run for six years and complement DFID’s current disability inclusion programming including UK Aid Connect.

The goal of this project is to ensure that all occupational drivers have access to good quality refractive error and referral services for reduction of avoidable blindness and improvement in road safety
The aim of this project is to control and eliminate blinding trachoma as a public health problem.

The overall objective is to ensure the equal participation of persons with disabilities and their organisations in socio-economic activities and community life and contribute to the achievement of the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) and the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (UNCRPD) in Bangladesh. Its three specific objectives are as follows: Specific objective 1: To strengthen the capacities and voice of DPOs/BPOs and increase their linkages and networking with state and non-state actors; Specific objective 2: To promote the full participation of persons with disabilities in socio-economic activities and improve their access to services; and Specific objective 3: To support local authorities and other government departments to meet their obligations for inclusive development as set out in the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (UNCRPD). These will assist to move towards disability inclusive development. Baseline survey, process documentation, KAP survey, participatory monitoring, community-rooted strategy and operation plan and action research will build evidence. Sustainability will be partly ensured by community resource pool. One component of the project aims to develop standard tools, guidelines, manuals, IEC materials and deliver training to support and explore possible areas of collaboration with academic institutes. The project has a component to support exploring VI & disability accessible ICT. Part of the project implemented by ABC and BVIPS is funded by the EC.
